        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Montreal</placeName>
                <date>27<hi rend="sup">th</hi> May 1862</date>.</p>
            <p>The <addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir—</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">The commencement of the College<lb/> recess gives me leisure to
                attend some what to<lb/> correspondence too much neglected. I have a<lb/> very
                respectable pile of letters before me of rather<lb/> antique date which testify and
                declare that I have<lb/> either been lazy these last few months, or my time<lb/> has
                been much occupied. I rather incline to the<lb/> latter supposition and I hope you
                will also—at<lb/> least I have had the wish to write you ere this.<lb/> With the
                resolution of years I find I have new<lb/> duties and new claims on my time. My
                    <add>בכור</add><lb/> must be examined occasionally to see how he<lb/> “gets on”
                at school where he learns English<lb/> grammar, arithmetic, French &amp;c and as I
                am<lb/> his Hebrew pedagogue at home, the young<lb/> gentleman (now <add>?</add> in
                his ninth year),<lb/> takes up a little of my time. The application<lb/> of this
                long interesting <add>הקדמה</add> I leave to yourself.<lb/> I have commenced, but
                not finished the Biography<lb/> of my late revered father <add>ע"ה</add> to which
                you</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>refer in your last. I have before written you that<lb/> I was asked for it elsewhere;
                though I should<lb/> be very pleased to see it in the Occident, and<lb/> shall
                certainly send you a copy duly authenticated<lb/> as you request. You are not, you
                write, a close<lb/> reader of the Jewish publications—neither am I.<lb/> I give you,
                as you requested me, credit for<lb/>
                <persName>Mr J. H. J's</persName> $3— Please inform me how our<lb/> account stands.
                I regret to say I am not quite<lb/> sure as to the Calendars I sent you.
                Besides<lb/> the dozen sent you per <persName>Miss S. J.</persName> (<date>21 May
                    '61</date>)<lb/> you had “ I reckon” another dozen. Please<lb/> let me know how
                the matter really is, as<lb/> though I made an entry some where, I cannot<lb/>
                remember where just now.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">As items of news (if such indeed<lb/> they be to you) I might
                mention that our<lb/> synagogue was reopened for the late holy days<lb/> after
                having been thoroughly renovated<lb/> internally. The cong. have been much<lb/>
                indebted to the pious zeal of <persName>Mrs Henry Benjamin</persName></p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>and <persName>Miss Sarah Joseph</persName> for the re-adornment<lb/> of their
                synagogue. <persName>Mrs. J. H. Joseph</persName> contributed<lb/> a very elegant
                Sepher Mantle and even the<lb/>
                <add>?</add> made a subscription among themselves<lb/> started by <persName>Miss D.
                    Benjamin</persName><lb/> and procured for the occasion a very handsome<lb/>
                cover for the readers desk and cloak for<lb/> one of the Sepharim. And those sums
                another time.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">The troubles in your distracted<lb/> country have caused
                    <persName>Poznanski</persName> of <placeName>Charleston</placeName><lb/> and his
                family to remain here for the last<lb/> eight months. He is not the terrible
                fellow<lb/> I took him for; and I fancy <persName>Messrs Lilienthal</persName><lb/>
                <persName>Einhorn</persName>
                <persName>Adler</persName> and one or two more are,<lb/> more mischievous than he
                was or ever will<lb/> be. <persName>Dr. Mayer</persName> of
                    <placeName>Albany</placeName> has been in here<lb/> once or twice—his wife who
                was arrested<lb/> in <placeName>Burlington</placeName> by the U. S. authorities is
                staying<lb/> here for a couple of months. I see no prospect<lb/> of a speedy
                reconstruction of the Union on<lb/> the old basis. I have no knowledge of the<lb/>
                <placeName>south</placeName> much, but I should scarcely think<lb/> they will allow
                themselves to be <hi rend="underline"><sic>whipt</sic></hi></p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>back, et afres<add>?</add>? <sic>our</sic> turn will come I presume<lb/> and we shall
                have northern invincibles<lb/> occupying <placeName>Montreal</placeName> n'est ce
                pas?</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">When we meet we can discuss<lb/> these weighty matters. Till then
                things, I presume<lb/> will go their way uninfluenced by what we<lb/> may say, so
                why vex ourselves therewith<add>?</add></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">During my recent visit to <placeName>England</placeName><lb/> I
                found that it was rather more common than I<lb/> expected, to <hi rend="underline"
                    >exchange</hi> publications. So if every you<lb/> want a few English's,
                Calendars, &amp;c on these terms (with<lb/> the usual discount, I shall be glad to
                supply you,<lb/> As I am sending on a parcel to <persName>Miss Gratz</persName>, I
                will<lb/> enclose you a few numbers of Part 1 of Sanatary<add>?</add><lb/>
                Institutions, recently put in paper covers which you<lb/> perhaps could circulate
                without much trouble<lb/> among your friends Jewish or Christian—selling<lb/> price
                25 cents a copy, with 20% off commission.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I have now pretty well covered my<lb/> paper, and must therefore bid
                you adieu for the<lb/> present. <persName>Mrs De Sola</persName> and family
                untie<lb/> in kind regards and with best wishes</p>
            <p rend="indent(7)">I remain yours truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(8)">
                <persName role="author">Abraham de Sola</persName>
            </p>
            <p>May I trouble you to send up to<lb/>
                <persName>Miss Gratz</persName> the copy<lb/> Sanatary<add>?</add> Institutions and
                parcel enclosed no doubt<lb/> you can always summons a <add>?</add><lb/>
                <add>?</add>evil at your <add>?</add></p>
        </body>
